Joseph Pine's career as a business coach began at IBM when he did something truly unorthodox: he brought business partners and customers into the development process of a new computer. Taking from this the lesson that every customer is unique, he wrote a book called Mass Customization on businesses that serve customers' unique needs. Later he discovered what he would coin the "Experience Economy" -- consumers buying experiences rather than goods or commodities -- and wrote a book of the same name.

Pine and his friend Jim Gilmore have since turned their focus to authenticity, which they argue is the main criterion people use when deciding what to buy. (The idea was featured in TIME's "10 Ideas That Are Changing the World," and also became a book.) They joke that their company, Strategic Horizons, ought to be called "Frameworks 'R' Us," after their specialty in helping others see business differently.

aws-transcripts.transcript: I'm talking about a very fundamental change that is going on in the very fabric of the modern economy and a top about that. I'm gonna go back to the beginning because in the beginning were commodities, commodities or things that you grow in the ground raising the ground of Palau, the ground basically animal, mineral, vegetable. And then you extract amount of the ground and sell them on the open marketplace. Commodities were the basis of the agrarian economy that lasted for millennia. But then along came the industrial revolution, and then goods became the predominant economic offering. Where we use commodities is the raw material to be able to make or manufacture goods. We moved from the grain economy to an industrial economy. But what then happened over the last 50 or 60 years is that goods have become commoditized commoditized, where they're treated like a commodity where people don't care who makes him. They just care about three things and three things only price, price and price. Now there's an antidote to commoditization, and that is customization. My first book was called Mass Customization. Came up a couple of times yesterday and how I discovered this progression of economic value was realizing that customizing a good automatically turn it into a service because it was done just for a particular person because it wasn't inventoried. It was delivered on demand to that individual person. So we moved from an industrial economy to a service based economy. But over the past 10 or 20 years, what's happened? Is it service's air being commoditized as well? Long distance telephone service sold on price, price price, fast food, restaurants all their value. Pricing on even the Internet is commoditized, not just goods, but service is as well. What that means is that it's time to move to a new level of economic value, time to go beyond the goods and the service's and using the same interesting what happens when you customize a service. What happens, You design a service that is so appropriate for a particular person. That's exactly what they needed This moment in time. Then you can't help but make them go. Wow, you can't help but turn into a memorable event. You can't help but turn into an experience. So we're shifting to an experience economy where experiences are becoming the predominant economic offering. Now, most places that I talked to. When I talk about experience, I talk about Disney at the world's premier experience Stager. I talk about theme restaurants, an experiential retail and boutique hotels in Las Vegas, the experience capital of the world. But here, when you think about experiences, think about Thomas, Toby and his group playing music. Think about meaningful places. Think about drinking wine, about a journey to the clock of the long. Now those air all experiences think about Ted itself, the experience capital. In the world of conferences, all of these are experiences, you know, The last several years I spent a lot of time in Europe and particularly in the Netherlands. Whenever I talk about the experience economy there, I'm always greeted at the end with one particular question. Almost invariably. And the question isn't really so much a question as an accusation and the Dutch when they usually put it, it always starts with the same two words. In other words, I mean you Americans as you Americans. You like your fantasy environment, your fake your Disneyland experiences. They say we Dutch, we like really natural, authentic experiences. So much so that happened is that I developed a fairly practice response, which is, I point out that first of all, you have to understand that there is no such thing as an inauthentic experience. Why? Because the experience happens inside of us. It's our reaction to the events or stage in front of us. So as long as we're in any sense, authentic human beings and every experience we have is authentic now there may be more or less natural artificial stimuli for the experience. But even that is a matter of degree, not kind. And there's no such thing is 100% natural experience.
